# Dart And Flutter

## Dart Style

- Follow `dart format` and Flutter lint conventions.
- Prefer immutable data models and `const` constructors where practical.
- Use descriptive names for playback, queue, timer, and provider concepts.
- Keep async work cancellable or lifecycle-aware; do not let disposed widgets receive callbacks.

## Flutter Structure

- Keep widgets focused on rendering and user interaction.
- Put playback, queue management, timers, permissions, file picking, cloud access, and persistence behind services or repositories.
- Group code by feature: player, timer, library, cloud sources, settings, and shared UI.
- Keep platform-specific code isolated behind interfaces so Android and iOS behavior can be tested separately.

## Audio Playback

- Support `.wav` playback as a first-class requirement.
- Never modify source music files. Do not transcode, normalize, tag, rename, move, delete, or rewrite user audio.
- Queue entries should reference a local file URI/path or a cloud provider object plus metadata stored by the app.
- Separate music playback mode from timer meditation mode; the end bell belongs to timer mode and must not mutate queued music.
- Handle interruptions, app lifecycle changes, and missing files with explicit user-facing states.

## Sources And Cloud Providers

- Treat local phone storage and cloud storage as read-only source providers.
- pCloud is the primary cloud provider target.
- Google Drive, OneDrive, and Dropbox should use the same provider abstraction instead of separate UI/business logic paths.
- Store OAuth tokens and provider credentials only in secure platform storage.
- Do not implement implicit upload, deletion, sync, or remote mutation unless explicitly requested.

## Testing

- Unit-test playback queue ordering, timer completion, bell selection, provider abstraction behavior, and error mapping.
- Widget-test core screens for loading, empty, error, active playback, and timer states.
- Mock platform plugins, file systems, and cloud providers in tests.
